paragraphs.text: A very informal contraction of ‘Got you.’ It’s like saying ‘I understand’ or ‘I see.’
Luke: Make sure you turn left at the third light, not the second one. [audio:phrases_verbs_gotcha_2]
Pailin: Okay, gotcha. So basically I turn left after the bank.
Pailin: We need to get to the yoga studio 10 minutes early ‘cause we need to sign a waiver. [audio:phrases_verbs_gotcha_3]
A conversational phrase to clarify some information. It’s often said before you give context or background information.
Luke: Why is this olive oil so much more expensive than this other one? [audio:phrases_verbs_you_see_2]
Pailin: Oh, you see, this one is extra virgin, so it has much more flavor.
Pailin: You seem to know a lot about vintage cars. [audio:phrases_verbs_you_see_3]
Luke: I do. You see, my grandpa used to work on them, so I grew up learning about them.
An informal phrase that refers to the relaxed and flexible approach to being on time, compared to many Western cultures. For example, friends meeting at 7PM might realistically mean 7:15 or later.
Pete will probably be a few minutes late. He’s usually on Thai time for events like this. [audio:phrases_verbs_thai_time_2]
My friend is always early, but I operate a bit more on a Thai time schedule. [audio:phrases_verbs_thai_time_3]
For something like a movie, TV show, or book to be released in movie theaters, streaming platforms, or in stores.
The last episode of the season is coming out this Friday! [audio:phrases_verbs_come_out1_2]
There are so many good movies coming out this summer. [audio:phrases_verbs_come_out1_3]
(LINK XX) See more uses of ‘Come out’
When it comes at the end of a statement, it’s a very casual way of saying ‘Do you agree?’
Looks like it’s going to rain later, huh? [audio:phrases_verbs_huh1_2]
That was a pretty good movie, huh? [audio:phrases_verbs_huh1_3]
A list of experiences or achievements a person hopes to accomplish before they die.
Visiting every continent is on the top of my bucket list. [audio:phrases_verbs_bucket_list_2]
Learning to play the guitar has been on my bucket list for years, but I just haven’t found the time. [audio:phrases_verbs_bucket_list_3]
Another way of saying ‘I’ll pay for it,’ usually for food or drinks.
Don’t worry about the bill, lunch is on me today. [audio:phrases_verbs_its_on_me_2]
You paid last time, so coffee is on me. [audio:phrases_verbs_its_on_me_3]
It’s a way of saying ‘I’m not joking.’ It shows that you’re being sincere.
Where did you guys hide my keys? Seriously, I need to leave for work now. Give them back to me please. [audio:phrases_verbs_seriously1_2]
Pineapple on pizza is actually good. No, seriously guys, you should try it. [audio:phrases_verbs_seriously1_3]
The name of the most popular app to transfer money to friends quickly. ‘Venmo’ is often used as a verb to mean someone will send money through Venmo.
I just Venmoed you for the lamp. Did you get it? [audio:phrases_verbs_venmo_3]
A phrase that means the amount mentioned before is the absolute maximum, and the actual amount is probably even less.
I only got three hours of sleep last night, if that. [audio:phrases_verbs_if_that_2]
He checks his email once a week, if that. [audio:phrases_verbs_if_that_3]
Can be said to show annoyance, like when you think the other person is saying something obvious or unnecessary
Luke: Pai, it’s 5 o’clock. We gotta leave now. [audio:phrases_verbs_i_know1_2]
Pailin: I know, I’m almost ready!
(LINK XX) See more uses of ‘I know’
A phrase said to show relief that something did or didn’t happen
Thank God I never have to take a class with that teacher again. She’s the worst! [audio:phrases_verbs_thank_god_2]
I thought I was going to miss my flight, but I made it just in time, thank God. [audio:phrases_verbs_thank_god_3]

A slang term used in a dating context. It means to suddenly stop texting or communicating with someone without an explanation, often leaving the other person confused and with no closure as to why things ended.
I’ve ghosted people before, and I’ve also been ghosted before. It’s just a part of the dating game. [audio:phrases_verbs_ghost_2]
Don’t ghost him! At least send him a text to end things politely. You don’t want things to be awkward if you run into him in public. [audio:phrases_verbs_ghost_3]
An informal phrase that means ‘I understand what you’re going through’ or ‘I agree with you because I can relate.’
Luke: I’m so exhausted from studying for finals all week. [audio:phrases_verbs_i_feel_you_2]
Pailin: I feel you. My brain feels so fried.
Luke: It’s so hard to find affordable 1-bedroom apartments in LA! [audio:phrases_verbs_i_feel_you_3]
Pailin: I feel you. The rent prices are just insane.

A slang term used in a dating context. It means to trick someone by using fake photos or a fake identity on dating apps. It can also be used when you trick someone by posting photos that are old or aren’t an accurate portrayal of how you currently look. It can be a noun or a verb.
It turned out her online boyfriend was actually a catfish living in another country. He was trying to scam her out of money. [audio:phrases_verbs_catfish_2]
I was catfished on my last date. The guy was a lot heavier than he looked in his photos. [audio:phrases_verbs_catfish_3]
Means face-to-face, rather than through the phone, email, video call, or through another person. It emphasizes a direct, physical interaction.
You can’t apply for the visa online - you need to apply for it in person at the embassy. [audio:phrases_verbs_in_person_2]
I’d rather break up with him in person than through text. [audio:phrases_verbs_in_person_3]
NOW THAT I THINK OF IT
Now that I think of it [audio:phrases_verbs_now_that_i_think_of_it_1]
A phrase said when a thought or idea has just come to your mind that’s usually triggered by the current conversation or situation.
My car’s making a weird noise. Oh, now that I think of it, I did hit a pothole yesterday. [audio:phrases_verbs_now_that_i_think_of_it_2]
I need to find a good book to read on vacation. Now that I think of it, my sister lent me one a while ago. [audio:phrases_verbs_now_that_i_think_of_it_3]
To start doing a task that needs to be done.
The broken fence still needs fixing, but I’ll get to it this weekend. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_to_it_2]
I have a lot of paperwork to get to before the end of the day. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_to_it_3]
I know I need to clean the garage, but I just haven’t gotten to it yet. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_to_it_4]
Cross my mind / cross your mind [audio:phrases_verbs_cross_my_mind_1]
For a thought or image of a person or idea to briefly enter your thoughts. This phrase implies it happened spontaneously and out of nowhere.
My old roommate from college crossed my mind yesterday. I wonder how he’s doing. [audio:phrases_verbs_cross_my_mind_2]
The idea of moving to another city has crossed my mind a few times lately. [audio:phrases_verbs_cross_my_mind_3]
Did it ever cross your mind that he might be lying to you? [audio:phrases_verbs_cross_my_mind_4]
Give me a call / give you a call [audio:phrases_verbs_give_me_a_call_1]
A casual phrase that means to call someone.
I’ll give you a call tomorrow morning to discuss the details. [audio:phrases_verbs_give_me_a_call_2]
Give me a call when you get this message. I want to talk to you about something. [audio:phrases_verbs_give_me_a_call_3]
A polite and slightly formal phrase said as a response to someone saying ‘Thank you.’
Pailin: Thanks for helping me find these items. [audio:phrases_verbs_my_pleasure_2]
Man: My pleasure! Glad I could help.
You can say this as you demonstrate how something should be done, or what something should look like.
He taught me to set up the tent like this, attaching the poles first. [audio:phrases_verbs_like_this_2]
Watch how I knead the dough. Push it forward, then fold it back, like this. [audio:phrases_verbs_like_this_3]
Get the hang of [something] / get the hang of [verb-ing] [audio:phrases_verbs_get_the_hang_of_1]
To become more comfortable with a new skill that’s difficult at first, until you can do it well.
Once you get the hang of parallel parking, it’s pretty easy. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_the_hang_of_2]
It took me a while to get the hang of riding a motorcycle, but now I don’t even have to think about it. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_the_hang_of_3]
I don’t think I’ll ever get the hang of speaking another language. [audio:phrases_verbs_get_the_hang_of_4]
To complete or finish something, especially when talking about work or some activity.
We’ve got to wrap up the meeting in ten minutes. [audio:phrases_verbs_wrap_up_2]
Let’s try to wrap up this discussion quickly so that we can move on to the next topic. [audio:phrases_verbs_wrap_up_3]
During the period before an anticipated event.
My new laptop won’t arrive until next week. In the meantime, I’ll have to use my old one. [audio:phrases_verbs_in_the_meantime_2]
We’re waiting to get approval for the building permits. In the meantime, we can start planning the interior design. [audio:phrases_verbs_in_the_meantime_3]
To spend time at a place or with a person casually.
The weather is so nice today. Do you want to hang out this evening, after I’m done with work? [audio:phrases_verbs_hang_out_2]
I love hanging out with them, but they live pretty far away, so I don’t see them often. [audio:phrases_verbs_hang_out_3]
When used to describe a person, it means they’re kind and very nice.
My neighbor is so sweet! She brought over a homemade pie to welcome us to the neighborhood. [audio:phrases_verbs_sweet_2]
A super sweet couple owns this bakery. They remember the name of everyone who comes through their door. [audio:phrases_verbs_sweet_3]

When used in a dating context, it’s a person who dates several people at once, as opposed to getting into long relationships. They’re usually considered very charming to be able to get others to fall for them romantically.
She warned me not to fall for him. I finally see that he’s just a player. All talk and no commitment. [audio:phrases_verbs_player_2]
I was a bit of a player in my college days, but that phase of my life is over now. [audio:phrases_verbs_player_3]
To start or establish a new business, office, or branch.
Our company is planning to open up a new office downtown next month. [audio:phrases_verbs_open_up_2]
Have you been to that new Thai restaurant that opened up on Sunset Boulevard? [audio:phrases_verbs_open_up_3]
To be clear and understandable, or logical and reasonable.
Does it really make sense to invest all of our money into just one stock? [audio:phrases_verbs_make_sense_2]
The ending of the book just didn’t make any sense. It felt rushed and out of place. [audio:phrases_verbs_make_sense_3]
In a dating context, it means to be going on dates with someone, but not yet with the labels of ‘boyfriend / girlfriend.’
Are you seeing anyone right now? [audio:phrases_verbs_seeing_someone_2]
I’ve been seeing this guy from my art class, and it’s going really well! I think there could be a future with him. [audio:phrases_verbs_seeing_someone_3]
An exaggerated way to say that a body part is hurting a lot.
My back is killing me. I think I slept in a weird position last night. [audio:phrases_verbs_killing_me_2]
My legs are killing me after pilates class. [audio:phrases_verbs_killing_me_3]
A phrase that shows sympathy to relate to someone else’s feelings or situation.
Luke: Getting into an accident on the freeway was one of the scariest moments of my life. [audio:phrases_verbs_i_can_imagine_2]
Pailin: I can imagine! Getting into an accident in general is scary enough.
Pailin: I worked six days in a row. I’m so exhausted. [audio:phrases_verbs_i_can_imagine_3]
Luke: I can imagine. You deserve a day off.
IF YOU DON’T MIND ME ASKING
A term of endearment, often used by older people to address someone younger. It can be used between people close to each other, but also between strangers.
What would you like for dinner, dear? [audio:phrases_verbs_dear_2]
Is everything okay, dear? You look a bit pale. [audio:phrases_verbs_dear_3]
The relatives of your spouse. Your spouse’s parents are your ‘mother-in-law’ and ‘father-in-law.’ Your spouse’s siblings are your ‘sister-in-law’ and ‘brother-in-law.’
I’m going to my sister-in-law’s baby shower today. [audio:phrases_verbs_in_laws_2]
My in-laws are so great. They’re like a second family to me. [audio:phrases_verbs_in_laws_3]
A shared meal where every guest brings a food dish to be shared by everyone.
We’re having a potluck at our house for the 4th of July, so start thinking about what dish you’ll bring! [audio:phrases_verbs_potluck_2]
The office organizes a monthly potluck lunch, and it’s always fun to see what everyone cooks. [audio:phrases_verbs_potluck_3]
When something is made without any pre-made ingredients or parts - it’s made entirely by someone without relying on kits or mixes.
This is my first time making a cake from scratch. It tastes great, but honestly, it wasn’t worth the effort. [audio:phrases_verbs_from_scratch_2]
When our business failed, we had to start all over again from scratch. [audio:phrases_verbs_from_scratch_3]

The word is a mix of ‘friends’ and ‘Thanksgiving.’ It’s a Thanksgiving-style meal with friends, instead of family. It’s especially common for young adults living far from family to host a Friendsgiving dinner since they can’t celebrate with family.
Instead of traveling home, my college friends and I are doing Friendsgiving together this year. [audio:phrases_verbs_friendsgiving_2]
What dish are you bringing to Friendsgiving this weekend? [audio:phrases_verbs_friendsgiving_3]
Luke: Can we meet at 7 instead of 6 tonight? [audio:phrases_verbs_for_sure_2]
Pailin: Could you pick up a tub of ice cream on your way home from work? [audio:phrases_verbs_for_sure_3]
Luke: For sure, vanilla or chocolate?
Means that someone made a wise decision or a good choice.
Luke: We should take the scenic route instead of the highway. [audio:phrases_verbs_good_call_2]
Pailin: Oh yeah, good call. The view will be much nicer.
Pailin: Let’s bring extra water for the hike. It’s going to be hot. [audio:phrases_verbs_good_call_3]
Luke: Good call, I almost forgot about that.
To be so annoyed with someone or something.
I’m so sick of hearing the same annoying ads on Spotify! [audio:phrases_verbs_sick_of_2]
I’m so sick of his excuses. [audio:phrases_verbs_sick_of_3]
Bring up [a topic] / bring it up [audio:phrases_verbs_bring_up_1]
To mention a topic or issue, or to introduce a subject for discussion.
When Sarah gets here, try not to bring up her ex. She’s still upset about him. [audio:phrases_verbs_bring_up_2]
He always brings up politics when we’re trying to have a chill dinner. It’s so frustrating! [audio:phrases_verbs_bring_up_3]
